1. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Weekly Updates
AN  - 639672472
T1  - Expert consensus on relevant risk predictors for the occurrence of cardiometabolic complications in pregnancy
T3  - International Congress on Obesity, ICO 2022. Melbourne, SA Australia.
A1  - Cowan S.
A1  - Lang S.
A1  - Enticott J.
A1  - Teede H.
A1  - Goldstein R.
A1  - Wang R.
A1  - Taylor F.
A1  - Moran L. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Obesity increases the risk of gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) and hypertensive disorders of pregnancy (HDP), including de novo gestational hypertension and preeclampsia. Early intervention with lifestyle treatment can prevent development or lessen severity of GDM and HDP, and reduce long-term risk of type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease. However, diagnosis of GDM and HDP occurs in the second-third trimester, and there is currently poor identification of high-risk women in early pregnancy. There is also no risk prediction model encompassing both GDM and HDP complications. The aim of this e-Delphi study was to reach an expert consensus on key predictors for cardiometabolic complications (GDM and HDP) in early pregnancy. MATERIALS AND METHODS: A narrative review was used to identify existing risk prediction models for GDM and HDP (1). Predictors used in these models were presented to key stakeholders (patient representatives, researchers and clinicians) for prioritisation using a two-round modified Delphi method (two e-surveys and one online consensus meeting). A priori consensus criteria informed which predictors were brought forward for discussion at the consensus meeting where the list of predictors was finalised. Discussions focused on the importance (clinically relevant and statistically significant), feasibility (easily and conveniently measured) and acceptability (suitable and appropriate to collect) of predictors. RESULT(S): The narrative review identified 18 GDM and 15 HDP prediction models. From these models 15 predictors were presented to stakeholders in round 1. All 15 predictors were brought forward from round 1 and eight additional predictors were nominated by stakeholders and discussed at the consensus meeting. Round 1 was completed by 31 stakeholders, 45% (14/31) of whom completed round 2. Twelve predictors were included in the final list, consisting of 10 maternal history predictors (age, body mass index, parity, ethnicity, history hypertension, history diabetes, family history diabetes, history polycystic ovary syndrome, history macrosomia, history chronic kidney disease), one biochemical predictor (blood glucose) and one hae-modynamic predictor (systolic blood pressure). Excluded predictors were viewed as impractical to collect in the clinical setting due to variability of measurement (e.g. waist circumference) and training required to ensure accuracy (e.g. uterine artery pulsatility index). CONCLUSION(S): This final list of predictors will be used to develop a risk prediction model for early pregnancy that facilitates timely intervention. Incorporating clinical knowledge and consumer perspectives in the early phase of predictor selection ensures that the risk prediction model is clinically useful with good practical performance, generating a tool that can be more easily integrated into routine care.
