AN  - 2021325740
T1  - Abstract #1318348: Association of THADA Gene Variants With Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome Clinical Manifestations in Women of Arab Ethnicity
T3  - The AACE Cardiometabolic Conference and the AACE Communities Middle East & North Africa (MENA) Conference. San Antonio United States.
A1  - Al-Khaduri M.
A1  - Ahmed A.
A1  - Zadjali F.
A1  - Al Farsi Y.
A1  - Tamimi Y. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Objective: Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is a complex endocrine disorder with genetic factors contributing to its etiology. Genome-wide association studies have identified variants at THADA gene that were shown to be associated with PCOS in Chinese and Europeans suggesting they may be important in the etiology of PCOS. However, the impact of these loci in other ethnicities remains to be determined. This is important as it may enable selection of suitable treatment or preventative options since women with PCOS have an increased risk of developing complications like diabetes and metabolic syndrome. Studies so far displayed the association between THADA gene and dyslipidemia. Also, rs7578597 SNP was shown to decrease insulin sensitivity in patients with the TT genotype and rs13429458 was significantly linked to hyperandrogenism. The objective of this study is to explore the association of four SNPs within the THADA gene with PCOS clinical manifestations in Omani Arab women. Method(s): We conducted a prospective study on 50 PCOS cases and 50 control Omani females in reproductive age from the gynecology clinic at the Sultan Qaboos University Hospital in Oman. A sample size of 49 cases and 49 controls was estimated for a significance level of 5% at 60% power, with minor allele frequencies of 12% and 1% in cases and controls. Cases fulfilled the Rotterdam criteria for PCOS. Controls were non pregnant women with no PCOS diagnosis. Patients with genetic disorders, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, androgen secreting tumors, Cushing syndrome, and hyperprolactinemia were excluded. Data collected included history, physical examination and laboratory results. Gene Panel Exome Sequencing was conducted on DNA extracted from blood samples for THADA and data analyzed using ANNOVAR software. Statistical analysis was performed using SPSS for descriptive statistics, Chi square test, and correlation analysis. Result(s): 12 nonsynonymous single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) were identified. Those SNPs with a mean allele frequency of less than 0.1 were excluded. rs35720761, rs33979934, rs7578597 and rs17031056 were tested for association with clinical, biochemical and physical parameters. Cases with dominant CC genotype (nonexposed group) of rs17031056 had an increased mean fasting blood sugar (P =.05) compared to CT and TT genotypes (exposed group) with HbA1C of 7.9 vs 5.5 (P =.39) however, there was no significant difference in mean values of Homeostatic Model Assessment of Insulin Resistance (HOMA-IR). Cases in the nonexposed group with rs35720761 and rs7578597 had higher AMH (38.2 vs 11.7 and 39.2 vs 16.1 pmol/L) and HbA1C values (7.1 vs 5.5) than exposed group. Also, for rs33979934, HbA1C was lower in the nonexposed than exposed group (5.6 vs 8.0), however the P value was not significant. There were no significant associations between physical or other biochemical parameters with the selected variants. Discussion/Conclusion: In conclusion, Arab women with PCOS and THADA CC genotype of rs17031056 had an increased level of fasting blood sugar. Larger studies in this population are required to further explore associations between metabolic manifestations in PCOS and specific gene variants.Copyright © 2022
