AN  - 639720425
T1  - USE OF TRANSIENT ELASTOGRAPHY IN PREGNANCY FOR THE NON-INVASIVE ASSESSMENT OF LIVER STEATOSIS AND STIFFNESS: PREDICTORS OF ELEVATED MEASUREMENTS
T3  - Annual Meeting of the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases, AASLD 2022. Virtual.
A1  - Lange M.
A1  - Caroll C.
A1  - Rosenbluth E.
A1  - Meislin R.
A1  - Sigel K.
A1  - Friedman S.L.
A1  - Terrault N.
A1  - Sperling R.
A1  - Kushner T. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: While liver biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosis of liver steatosis and fibrosis, it introduces excess risk in pregnancy. Transient elastography (TE), a non-invasive test, is not currently approved for use in pregnancy due to limited data. We assessed the utility and diagnostic value of TE during pregnancy and determined predictors of elevated liver stiffness (LSM) and CAP steatosis. Method(s): As part of a larger prospective study using ultrasound (u/s) to diagnose nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), pregnant women presenting for routine prenatal care were recruited. Liver sonograms were obtained at 18-22weeks gestation. Fibroscan (Echosens, France) was performed by two trained operators at 24-32weeks gestation. CAP was graded: <240 dB/m (grade 0), 240-270 dB/m (grade 1), 270-300 dB/m (grade 2) and >300 dB/m (grade 3). LSM cutoffs were: <=7 kPa (F0-F1, none), 7.5 - 10 kPa (F2, mild), 10-14 kPa (F3, significant) and >14 kPa (F4, advanced). Multivariate linear regression was used to evaluate the association of various factors with LSM or CAP. Result(s): Of 209 enrolled patients, TE was performed on 78 (37%). Non-adherence to a minimum 3 hr fast was the most common reason for being unable to perform TE (54.5%). Mean age and pre-pregnancy BMI were 29.7years (SD6.1) and 31.7 kg/m2 (SD5.7) respectively. Patients were 47.4% Hispanic, 43.6% Black, 3.9% White, and 2.6% Asian. Prior medical history included 11.6% with chronic hypertension, 6.4% with diabetes, and 3.9% with polycystic ovary syndrome. None of the patients had a known history of liver disease and 61% denied alcohol use prior to pregnancy. TE was performed at mean 26weeks (SD3.6) gestation with M size probe used most frequently (86%). Mean fasting time was 5.2 hours (SD3.4). Ninety-five percent of scans had an IQR/med% below the recommended 30%. Mean LSM was 5.1 kPa (SD1.9), and 9.5% had a score of F2 or more. Mean CAP was 224.1 dB/m (SD43.6), with 30.8% being at least Grade 1. On multivariate analysis, chronic hypertension (p=0.01) and pre-eclampsia (p=0.02) were significant predictors for LSM. Pre-pregnancy BMI was a significant predictor of CAP (p<0.001) (Table 1). Among study participants, 8 (10.8%) had hepatic steatosis on u/s, all Grade 1. The sensitivity, specificity, PPV, and NPV of CAP in detecting hepatic steatosis compared to standard u/s was 37.5%, 69.7%, 13%, and 90.2% respectively. AUROC was 0.54, indicating suboptimal discrimination. Conclusion(s): In one of the largest studies evaluating TE in pregnancy, we demonstrated that TE may be a feasible and effective method of ruling out hepatic steatosis. Chronic hypertension and pre-eclampsia were associated with higher LSM in pregnancy. CAP was associated with elevated BMI. Inconsistencies in the assessment of steatosis in pregnancy by CAP and u/s may be attributable to gestational age-dependent changes in the liver. Future studies should perform TE longitudinally and assess for potential obstetrical confounders.
