100. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639364394
T1  - ASSOCIATION OF OBESITY AND OBESITY-RELATED CONDITIONS WITH THYROID CANCER RISK IN THE SISTER STUDY COHORT
T3  - 91st Annual Meeting of the American Thyroid Association, ATA 2022. Montreal, QC Canada.
A1  - Pasqual E.
A1  - O'Brien K.
A1  - Rinaldi S.
A1  - Sandler D.
A1  - Kitahara C. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Obesity has been associated with an increased risk of thyroid cancer (TC), but the underlying mechanisms remain poorly understood. We prospectively examined the associations of excess adiposity and obesity-related metabolic conditions with risk of TC in a large cohort study of U.S. women. METHOD(S): The Sister Study is a prospective cohort of 50,844 U.S women aged 35-74 at enrolment (2003-2009) with followup for cancer incidence through 2019. At enrolment, height, weight, waist, hip circumference, and blood pressureweremeasured by trained personnel, and medical and pharmacological histories were selfreported through telephone interview. Dyslipidemia, hypertension, and type-2 diabetes were defined as reporting either the physician diagnosis or the use of their disease-specific medication. Metabolic syndrome was defined as having waist circumference >80cm and at least two of the following self-reported conditions: diabetes/borderline diabetes, dyslipidemia, hypertension, or measured systolic blood pressure >=130mmHg or diastolic >=85mmHg. We investigated the association of TC incidence with excess adiposity (body mass index [BMI], waist, and waist-to-hip ratio), obesity-related metabolic conditions (type-2 diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidemia, metabolic syndrome, polycystic ovary syndrome [PCOS], hypothyroidism), and metformin use, using Cox proportional hazards regression models with age as time variable. To evaluate the potential for surveillance bias and avoid inclusion of potential baseline TC, women with baseline thyroid nodule (n = 3,590) were excluded in a sensitivity analysis. RESULT(S): Among 46,574 cancer-free women at baseline, there were 215 TC diagnosed during follow-up (median = 11.3; max = 15.7 years). Increased TC rates were associated with measured baseline BMI (hazard ratio [HR]for 5 Kg/m2-increased = 1.20, 95%CI = 1.08-1.34), waist circumference (HR>88cm vs <80cm = 1.63, 95%CI = 1.20-2.23), and waist-to hip ratio (HR>0.85 vs <0.85 = 1.49, 95%CI = 1.11-1.99), but not with blood pressure. TC risk was elevated among women with (versus not) metabolic syndrome (HR = 1.64, 95%CI = 1.13-2.38), hypertension (HR = 1.71, 95%CI = 1.27-2.30), and PCOS (HR = 2.37, 95%CI = 1.35-4.19). After excluding baseline thyroid nodules, TC risk was lower in women with hypothyroidism (HR = 0.54 95%CI 0.31-0.94). CONCLUSION(S): This work confirm previous reported association between excess adiposity indicators and increased TC risk in a large population of U.S. women. Our findings suggest that metabolic syndrome, hypertension, PCOS, and hypothyroidism may influence TC risk independently of obesity.
