AN  - 638129289
T1  - DIMINISHED OVARIAN RESERVE AND HIGHER BLOOD GLUCOSE LEVELS AMONG SUBFERTILE WOMEN
T3  - 77th Scientific Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, ASRM 2021. Baltimore, MD United States.
A1  - Minguez-Alarcon L.
A1  - Souter I.
A1  - Sacha C.
A1  - Dimitriadis I.
A1  - Hammer K.C.
A1  - Williams P.L.
A1  - Ford J.B.
A1  - Rexrode K.M.
A1  - Hauser R.
A1  - Chavarro J.E. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: To investigate the association of antral follicle count (AFC), as a reliable marker of ovarian reserve, with subsequent blood glucose levels, as a measure of glucose tolerance, among subfertile women. MATERIALS AND METHODS: This analysis included 212 women (252 glucose levels) enrolled in the prospective Environment and Reproductive Health (EARTH) Study cohort at Massachusetts General Hospital Fertility Center (2005-2017) who had data available on AFC (assessed by transvaginal ultrasonography within a year of study enrolment) and glucose levels (measured in blood as part of routine medical care). AFC measures were obtained a median of 4 years prior to glucose measurements (range 1 month - 13 years). We excluded two women with diagnosed diabetes. We used AFC as a categorical variable [<7 (18% women), 7-11 (35% women), >11 (47% women)]. We natural log transformed glucose levels to more closely approximate a normal distribution. We used multivariable linear regression models to evaluate the association of AFC and glucose levels using a random intercept to account for correlation in outcomes across multiple observations per woman while adjusting for age, body mass index (BMI), smoking, infertility diagnosis, family history of diabetes, physical activity and polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS). We performed a sensitivity analysis excluding women diagnosed with PCOS. RESULT(S): Women had a median (IQR) BMI of 23.4 years (21.4, 26.3) and age of 36 kg/m2 (33, 39). Median (IQR) AFC was 8 (11, 16) and glucose levels were 88 (81, 96) mg/dL. Lower AFC was associated with higher glucose levels (p, trend=0.03). Specifically, adjusted mean glucose levels (95% CI) decreased across increasing AFC categories: 93.4 (88.9, 98.1), 86.3 (83.5, 89.3) and 89.3 (86.7, 92.0) mg/dL, respectively. We observed similar results after excluding 20 women (9%) diagnosed with PCOS. CONCLUSION(S): Among subfertile women seeking fertility care, those with AFC <7 (diminished ovarian reserve, DOR) had higher glucose levels than women with higher AFC. These results suggest that women with low ovarian reserve may be at higher risk of glucose intolerance and adds to the increasing literature showing associations of fertility measures with cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk factors. IMPACT STATEMENT: CVD is the leading cause of death among U.S. women, accounting for approximately 1 of every 3 female deaths. While traditional CVD risk factors include diabetes, smoking, and obesity, accumulating evidence has identified pregnancy complications as well as fertility measures as emerging CVD risk factors in women. Results from this analysis may help identify women at risk for CVD.
