T1  - Abstract #1002545: Prediction of Gut Microbial Community Structure and Function in Polycystic Ovary Syndrome with High Low-density Lipoprotein Cholesterol
T3  - AACE Annual Meeting 2021. Virtual, Online.
A1  - zhu X.
A1  - Li Y.
A1  - Jiang Y.
A1  - Zhang J.
A1  - Duan R.
A1  - Liu L.
A1  - Liu C.
A1  - Xu X.
A1  - Yu L.
A1  - Wang Q.
A1  - Xiong F.
A1  - Ni C.
A1  - Xu L.
A1  - He Q. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Objective: Gut microbiota has been proved to be involved in the occurrence and development of many diseases, such as type 2 diabetes, obesity, coronary heart disease, etc. It provides a new idea for the pathogenesis of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS).Our purpose was to collect the data of sex hormone metabolism, glucose metabolism, lipid metabolism, gut microbiota diversity, analyzed the correlation between clinical data and gut microbiota, analyzed the differences in gut microbiota between groups, and predicted the function of different gut microbiota and the metabolic pathways that may be involved. Method(s): 18 healthy premenopausal women (group CON ), 20 PCOS women with low low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDLC)(group L_LDLC), and 16 PCOS with high LDLC(group H_LDLC) were enrolled according to " Guidelines for prevention and treatment of dyslipidemia in Chinese adults".PCR amplification technology was used to collect the purified amplicons at the same molar concentration, and terminal sequencing was performed on Illumina Miseq PE300 platform to complete fecal DNA extraction and sequencing. The clinical data were calculated by SPSS statistical software package 20.0. All statistical tests were double-tailed. When p < 0.05, the difference was statistically significant. Alpha diversity and betaeta diversity were used to describe the change of gut microbiota between groups.Spearman correlation coefficient was used to evaluate the potential correlation between gut microbial community and clinical parameters.ROC Curve was made to reveal the relationship between sensitivity and specificity of gut microbiota. COG, KEGG and Phylogenetic Investigation of Communities by Reconstruction of Unobserved States (PICRUSt) were used to predict the functional profile of gut microbial communities. Result(s): Our study showed that the gut microbial community of PCOS with high low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDLC) has a noticeable imbalance, mainly manifested by the decrease of alpha-diversity, the change of beta-diversity, the increase of pro-inflammatory bacteria and the decrease of healthy symbiotic bacteria. We can distinguish healthy people from PCOS patients or PCOS subtypes using characteristic gut microbiota. In PCOS with high LDLC, carbohydrate, lipid, amino acid metabolism, and inflammation-related pathways were most significantly changed, suggesting that gut microbiota may participate in the disease's occurrence and development through these pathways. Discussion/Conclusion: In conclusion, this is the first report on the gut microbiota of PCOS with high LDLC, suggesting that in the drug development or treatment of PCOS patients, the difference of gut microbiota in PCOS patients with different LDLC levels should be fully considered.Copyright © 2021
