169. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 636199568
T1  - Metformin versus insulin in early pregnancy and risk of congenital malformations
T3  - 37th International Conference on Pharmacoepidemiology and Therapeutic Risk Management. Virtual.
A1  - Kjerpeseth L.J.
A1  - Cesta C.E.
A1  - Engeland A.
A1  - Furu K.
A1  - Gissler M.
A1  - Gulseth H.L.
A1  - Karlstad O.
A1  - Kieler H.
A1  - Leinonen M.K.
A1  - Norgaard M.
A1  - Pazzagli L.
A1  - Selmer R.
A1  - Zoega H.
A1  - Cohen J.M. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: Metformin is increasingly used in pregnant women with type 2 diabetes (T2D). However, evidence is lacking on its safety for rare outcomes such as major congenital malformations (MCM). Unlike insulin, which is considered safe in pregnancy, metformin crosses the placenta in concentrations approaching that of maternal circulation. Objective(s): To investigate whether metformin exposure in first trimester increases the risk of MCM compared with insulin exposure. Method(s): In a cohort study, we pooled individually linked data on ~3.3 million pregnancies from nationwide registers on births, prescriptions, specialist healthcare and deaths in Iceland (2004-2017), Norway (2004-2017), Sweden (2006-2016) and Finland (1996-2016). Pregnancies resulting in singleton births exposed to insulin or metformin in first trimester were included. To focus on women with T2D, which is underrecorded in the data, we excluded women with type 1 diabetes (T1D), polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) or fertility treatment (ART). We also excluded pregnancies with exposure to other glucose-lowering or teratogenic drugs in first trimester or a diagnosis of teratogenic infection or genetic anomaly in the offspring. In the primary analysis, pregnancies exposed to both insulin and metformin were assigned to the metformin group. We did secondary analyses of exposure to metformin only and to both metformin and insulin. The comparisons were repeated in sensitivity analyses restricted to women with a T2D diagnosis. Using logbinomial regression with stratum-specific weights based on propensity score stratification, we estimated the risk ratio (RR) for MCM in the offspring diagnosed within 1 year of birth. Result(s): We identified 21,398 pregnancies exposed to insulin or metformin in first trimester. After excluding 13,714, 1996 and 736 women with T1D, PCOS and ART, respectively, 4285 pregnancies were included; 2910 exposed to metformin, 1087 insulin and 288 both. An MCM occurred in 143 (4.5%) pregnancies exposed to metformin +/- insulin and 71 (6.8%) pregnancies exposed to insulin only, yielding a crude RR of 0.67. Compared to insulin only, the adjusted RR for metformin +/- insulin was 0.73 (95% CI 0.45-1.16), for metformin only 0.68 (95% CI 0.43-1.07) and for metformin + insulin 1.12 (95% CI 0.69-1.82). Restricting the study population to the 1434 women with a T2D diagnosis yielded point estimates closer to one for all comparisons, albeit with wider confidence intervals. Conclusion(s): We did not find evidence of an increased risk of MCM with the use of metformin in pregnancy. The results should be interpreted with caution since we do not have information on glycemic control, which is an important risk factor for MCM.
