A1  - Yang H. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Objective: To explore the correlation between neck circumference (NC) and the prevalence of metabolic syndrome (MetS) and assess the predictive value of NC for MetS in women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Material(s) and Method(s): This is a cross-sectional study recruited four hundred forty-one women diagnosed with PCOS from January 2018 to January 2021. Anthropometric parameters, neck circumference, blood pressure, reproductive hormones, glycemic and lipid profile were measured in all subjects. The definition of MetS adopted in this study was the International Diabetes Federation (IDF) criteria. Result(s): Of the 441 subjects, MetS was diagnosed in 119 women (26.98%). PCOS women with larger NC had significantly greater values of body weight, body mass index (BMI), waist circumference (WC), hip circumference (HC), waist to hip ratio (WHR), systolic blood pressure, diastolic blood pressure, fasting blood glucose, fasting insulin, homeostasis model assessment of insulin resistance (HOMA-IR), homeostasis model assessment of beta cell function (HOMA-beta), triglyceride and high-density lipoprotein cholesterol. The prevalence of MetS, hypertention, obesity, central obesity, hyperglycemia and dyslipidaemia was also significantly higher in women with larger NC. Additionally, logistic regression analysis showed that women in the highest quartile of NC had the highest prevalence of MetS (RR=7.14, 95%CI: 1.82-28.01) after adjusting for confounding factors. Furthermore, NC was able to identify MetS in women with PCOS. The optimal cut-off points were 33.0 cm (Youden index = 0.44). The area under the curve in predicting MetS by NC, BMI, WC and WHR was comparable. Conclusion(s): Neck circumference is positively correlated with the incidence of MetS in women with PCOS and had similar predictive value for MetS compared with BMI, WC and WHR. Impact Statement: This study is the first to assess the effects of NC as a parameter in the prediction of metabolic syndrome in women with PCOS. The strengths of our study lie in that the simple and standardized measuring method of neck circumference, as well as the validated and complete metabolic data make our findings highly applicable to the clinical practice. Therefore, we suggest NC as a simple, reliable and applicable anthropometric measure to be used in the routine clinical assessment of women with PCOS to screen those at high risk of MetS.Copyright © 2021
