217. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2004456161
T1  - 989: Universal HbA1c screening versus conventional risk factor screening for the prediction of gestational diabetes
T3  - SMFM 40th Annual Meeting-The Pregnancy Meeting. Grapevine United States.
A1  - Bender W.
A1  - McCarthy C.
A1  - Chittams J.
A1  - Elovitz M.A.
A1  - Parry S.
A1  - Durnwald C. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Objective: To compare the accuracy of conventional risk factor (CRF) based screening versus universal hemoglobin A1c(HbA1c) screening in diagnosing gestational diabetes (GDM). Study Design: This is a retrospective cohort study of women undergoing universal HbA1c screening at < 17 weeks' gestation between December 2016 and April 2018 at a single urban tertiary care center. Women with preexisting diabetes or HbA1c > 6.5% were excluded. Women with HbA1c < 5.7% did routine 2-step 3rd trimester GDM screening. Women with HbA1c 5.7- 6.4% underwent early 2-step GDM screening. Positive screens were diagnosed with early GDM. Normal early screeners underwent repeat 3rd trimester screening. CRFs for early GDM screening at our institution prior to universal screening were history of GDM, body mass index (BMI) > 40 kg/m2, prior macrosomia (Birth weight > 4000g), prior stillbirth, and polycystic ovary syndrome. The predictive ability of universal HbA1c screening compared to that of CRF was evaluated by testing for differences in the area under the curve (AUC) of receiver operating curves (ROCs) and a non-inferiority test. Result(s): 3072 women had universal HbA1c screening, and 1921 women met inclusion criteria. 296 (15.4%) women had >1 CRFs. See Table 1 for demographics. Seventy-nine (26.7%) of women with CRFs had HbA1c >5.7% compared to 158 (9.7%) of women without CRFs. The rate of both early GDM and 3rd trimester GDM were higher in the women with CRFs compared to those without CRFs (2.7 v. 0.7%, p = 0.002 and 11.5 vs. 4.8%, p < 0.001, respectively). The AUC of CRF screening and HbA1c > 5.7% were 0.71 and 0.75, respectively (p = 0.07) after controlling for race, BMI, maternal age, and insurance (Fig 1). A non-inferiority test indicated that HbA1c screening is not inferior to CRF screening based on the percentage of concordant pairs achieved with GDM diagnosis (CRF 82%; HbA1c 85%, p < 0.001). Conclusion(s): Universal HbA1c screening performs as favorably as CRF screening for the prediction of GDM and may be a more acceptable screening strategy for women and clinicians. [Formula presented] [Formula presented]Copyright © 2019
