T1  - Performance of a computable phenotype for identification of patients with diabetes within PCORnet: The Patient-Centered Clinical Research Network
A1  - Wiese A.D.
A1  - Roumie C.L.
A1  - Buse J.B.
A1  - Guzman H.
A1  - Bradford R.
A1  - Zalimeni E.
A1  - Knoepp P.
A1  - Morris H.L.
A1  - Donahoo W.T.
A1  - Fanous N.
A1  - Epstein B.F.
A1  - Katalenich B.L.
A1  - Ayala S.G.
A1  - Cook M.M.
A1  - Worley K.J.
A1  - Bachmann K.N.
A1  - Grijalva C.G.
A1  - Rothman R.L.
A1  - Chakkalakal R.J. 
AO  - Wiese, Andrew D.; ORCID: https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0699-4224
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Purpose: PCORnet, the National Patient-Centered Clinical Research Network, represents an innovative system for the conduct of observational and pragmatic studies. We describe the identification and validation of a retrospective cohort of patients with type 2 diabetes (T2DM) from four PCORnet sites. Method(s): We adapted existing computable phenotypes (CP) for the identification of patients with T2DM and evaluated their performance across four PCORnet sites (2012-2016). Patients entered the cohort on the earliest date they met one of three CP categories: (CP1) coded T2DM diagnosis (ICD-9/ICD-10) and an antidiabetic prescription, (CP2) diagnosis and glycosylated hemoglobin (HbA1c) >=6.5%, or (CP3) an antidiabetic prescription and HbA1c >=6.5%. We required evidence of health care utilization in each of the 2 prior years for each patient, as we also developed an incident T2DM CP to identify the subset of patients without documentation of T2DM in the 365 days before t0. Among a systematic sample of patients, we calculated the positive predictive value (PPV) for the T2DM CP and incident-T2DM CP using electronic health record (EHR) review as reference. Result(s): The CP identified 50 657 patients with T2DM. The PPV of patients randomly selected for validation was 96.2% (n = 1572; CI:95.1-97.0) and was consistently high across sites. The PPV for the incident-T2DM CP was 5.8% (CI:4.5-7.5). Conclusion(s): The T2DM CP accurately and efficiently identified patients with T2DM across multiple sites that participate in PCORnet, although the incident T2DM CP requires further study. PCORnet is a valuable data source for future epidemiological and comparative effectiveness research among patients with T2DM.Copyright © 2019 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.
