257. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630921809
T1  - Development and validation of a risk prediction model for cardiovascular disease in women of reproductive age
T3  - American Heart Association Scientific Sessions, AHA 2019. Philadelphia, PA United States.
A1  - Grandi S.M.
A1  - Filion K.B.
A1  - Hutcheon J.A.
A1  - Smith G.N.
A1  - Platt R.W. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Currently available risk prediction scores for cardiovascular disease (CVD) were developed in older age populations, which limits their ability to provide accurate estimates of risk in younger women. Moreover, these risk scores do not incorporate pregnancy complications that have been shown to be associated with long-term risk of CVD. This study aims to develop and validate a CVD risk prediction model in women of reproductive age that accounts for obstetrical history. Method(s): A cohort of 502,916 women aged 15-45 years with a recorded delivery from April 1999 to March 2017 in the United Kingdom's Clinical Practice Research Datalink database was created to develop the models for screening within the first year post-partum. The primary outcome was CVD defined as coronary artery disease, coronary revascularization, cerebrovascular disease, myocardial infarction, peripheral vascular disease, unstable angina, and CVD-related death. Candidate predictors were chosen based on clinical and substantive knowledge. The Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator method and an accelerated failure time model was used to determine the inclusion of predictors and to estimate the final model. Internal validation via bootstrapping was used to estimate the optimism-corrected measures of model accuracy and performance. Result(s): A total of 2,744 women experienced a cardiovascular event over a median follow-up of 3.2 years (Interquartile range: 1.5-7.5). Predictors in the final model included traditional CVD risk factors along with social deprivation, polycystic ovary syndrome, prior use of oral contraceptives, depression, thyroid disorders, hypertensive disorders of pregnancy, gestational diabetes, preterm birth, small-for-gestational-age birth, infertility, parity, and history of pregnancy complications. The optimism-corrected model had modest discrimination (C-statistic: 0.67, 95% CI 0.66, 0.69) and good calibration and performance (calibration slope: 0.98; Nagelkerke R 0.07). Conclusion(s): Although the model showed modest predictive accuracy and performance, the findings highlight the importance of including pregnancy-related and sex-specific risk factors for CVD risk prediction in women of reproductive age.
