262. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001819115
T1  - Prevalence of gestational diabetes in our sanitary area
T3  - 23rd IFCC-EFLM European Congress of Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine. Barcelona Spain.
A1  - Balsalobre E.L.
A1  - Camacho I.P.
A1  - Penas M.D.M.V.
A1  - Ortiz A.M. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background-aim: Gestational Diabetes (GD)is the most frequent metabolic disease associated with pregnancy, with a prevalence between 2-15%. For the screening of this pathology, the O'Sullivan test is performed between week 24 and 28 of gestation, and if it is pathological (glucose at 60 minutes higher than 150 mg/dL)confirmation is necessary with the performance of the so-called Oral Glucose Tolerance Test (TTOG). The diagnosis of DG is based on presenting 2 or more points of the TTOG above the established cut-off point (GluBasal <105 mg/dL, Glu60 <190 mg/dL, Glu120 <165 mg/dL, Glu180 <145 mg/dL). The presence of a series of factors, determines a higher incidence of this pathology such as maternal age over 30 years, obesity, family history of diabetes, personal history of prediabetes and polycystic ovarian syndrome among others. The objective of this study was to estimate the prevalence of GD in our health area and the possible risk factors that could be related. Method(s): A descriptive, retrospective study in which the GD screenings were carried out on 6181 pregnant women during a period of 2 years (December 2015 to December 2017). The mean age of the study population was 33.5 years, and the average weight was 63.2 kg. The glucose determinations were performed on a Cobas 6000 analyzer from Roche Diagnostics using photometry. Result(s): Of the total number of patients studied, 1938 had a positive O'Sullivan test and 108 (1.74%)of them confirmed the diagnosis of GD with TTOG. The mean age of the pregnant women with a diagnosis of GD was 35.9 years and the average weight was 66.5 Kg. Conclusion(s): -The prevalence of GD in our health area is slightly lower than that published in similar studies (2-15%). -The O'Sullivan test has a low specificity in the diagnosis of GD, which implies a delay in the diagnosis and an increase in health expenditure. -The factors age and weight demonstrate their influence on the development of GD so they should be considered when interpreting the results of the screening test together with a correct anamnesis to be able to identify the most susceptible pregnant women to develop this pathology in order to establish treatment as early as possible and thus avoid possible complications.Copyright © 2019
