263. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001783618
T1  - Self-administered questionnaire to screen for polycystic ovarian syndrome
T3  - Sixty-Seventh Annual Meeting of the Pacific Coast Reproductive Society. Indian Wells United States.
A1  - Bedrick B.S.
A1  - Eskew A.M.
A1  - Chavarro J.E.
A1  - Jungheim E.S. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrinopathy affecting reproductive aged women. However, it is often underdiagnosed. Given the long-term health risks associated with PCOS, such as infertility, diabetes, and endometrial cancer, it is important to optimize accurate diagnosis. A self-reported questionnaire that identifies women who should undergo clinical screening for PCOS could reduce the number of women who go undiagnosed and untreated and would also facilitate research on risk factors for this condition. Objective(s): The objective of this study is to validate a self-administered questionnaire to identify women at risk for PCOS. [Figure presented] Material(s) and Method(s): Women aged 18 to 50 years with and without a diagnosis of PCOS were enrolled in this case-control study. Confirmation of PCOS diagnosis was made through medical chart review. Each woman completed a survey, which included questions on cycle length and regularity, use of combined hormonal contraceptives (COCs), acne in the previous 3 months, and depilatory practices. Women selected the image corresponding to the extent of their terminal hair growth in the six body regions from the modified Ferriman-Gallway (FG) scale that are easiest to self-assess and most strongly associated with hirsutism: upper lip, chin, chest, upper and lower abdomen, and thighs. Hirsutism was defined as a simplified FG (sFG) score of >=3 summed over the upper lip and lower and upper abdomen.1 Chi-square, Fisher's exact, and Wilcoxon rank-sum tests were used to compare groups. Sensitivity and specificity for testing for PCOS were calculated for hirsutism as indicated by sFG, individual body regions,2 and depilatory practices. Logistic regression models were used to assess the value of including multiple variables in screening. Result(s): Fifty-one women with PCOS and 50 controls were enrolled. There was no significant difference in age or COC use between the groups. The majority of women (76%) with PCOS had an sFG score indicative of hirsutism, compared to 30% of women without PCOS (p< 0.0001). Compared to women without PCOS, women with PCOS had higher scores for hair growth in four regions: chin, upper lip, lower abdomen (p<0.0001) and thighs (p <0.01). Women with PCOS were more likely to shave, wax, or bleach (SWB) hair in male-patterned areas than women without PCOS (p<0.0001) but were no more likely to use electrolysis. Hirsutism could predict PCOS diagnosis with 76% sensitivity and 70% specificity (Table 1) and having either a positive sFG score or SWB had a sensitivity of 83% and specificity of 66%. In multivariate analysis, women with hirsutism were 3x as likely to have PCOS as those without hirsutism (OR 3.3; 95% CI 1.1, 9.7, p=0.035) and women who SWB hair in male-patterned regions were 4x as likely to have PCOS as those who did not (OR 4.1; 95% CI 1.4, 12.3, p=0.011). Additional variables did not enhance the model. Conclusion(s): Self-report of male-patterned hair terminal distribution using a brief questionnaire may be an effective screening tool for PCOS. Funding(s): TL1TR002344. References: 1 Cook, Heather, et al. "Reanalyzing the modified Ferriman-Gallwey score: is there a simpler method for assessing the extent of hirsutism?" Fertility and sterility. 96,5(2011):1266-70.e1. 2 Knochenhauer, Eric S., et al. "Examination of the chin or lower abdomen only for the prediction of hirsutism." Fertility and sterility. 74,5(2000):980-983.Copyright © 2019
