267. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631098581
T1  - A biochemical and molecular study of tumor necrosis factor-a in female with polycystic ovarian syndrome
A1  - Al-Assadi N.A.M.
A1  - AL-Shaikh S.F.
A1  - Al-Qaysi S.A. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is one of the most common endocrine dysfunctions in women of reproductive age. it isrefers to a heterogeneous group of gynecologic disorders with variable degrees of ovarian and adrenal hyperandrogenism. Tumor necrosis factor-a are related with gynecological pathologies including preeclampsia, endometriosis and PCOS. Insulin resistance and TNF-a was measured from fasting glucose, TNF-a gene polymorphisim estimation using PRC-RFLPin a group of 50 PCOS females and 50 age compare with healthy controls. The age in both study groups no significant difference for patients (22.44 +/- 3.20) and controls (23.34 +/- 2.95). All the PCOS had elevated body mass index (27.70 +/- 5.07), waist to hip ratio (0.85 +/- 0.04), fasting insulin (10.76 +/- 2.86), homeostatic model assessment (HOMA) score (3.18 +/- 1.14) and serum TNF-a (23.19 +/- 3.95), when compared with controls. There was a significant (r=0.244, P=0.01), (r=0.293, P=0.003) positive correlation of IR with BMI and waist to hip ratio, respectively. Also, a significantly (r=0.543, P<0.001) positivecorrelation were found between TNF-a and insulin resistance. Genotype distribution for the C-850T polymorphism was observed with the frequency of the variant T allele being 16% in the PCOS group and 6% in the control group (p>0.11). In conclusion, present examinations suggested that the TNF-a might contribute to the pathogenesis of PCOS, being the basis of increase body weight which lead to development of insulin resistance. While the incidence of PCOS independent of a polymorphism of the TNF-a C850T (rs 1799724) in population studied.Copyright © 2018 The authors.
