291. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623113508
T1  - Oral glucose tolerance test is more sensitive than glycated hemoglobin for prediabetes and diabetes diagnosis in PCOS women
T3  - 100th Annual Meeting of the Endocrine Society, ENDO 2018. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - Crespo R.P.
A1  - Rocha T.M.P.
A1  - Costa F.C.
A1  - Mendonca B.B.
A1  - Bachega T.A.
A1  - Gomes L.G. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - BACKGROUND: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disorder associated with an increased risk of insulin resistance, prediabetes and type 2 diabetes (T2D). Oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) is recommended for screening of prediabetes and T2D in the PCOS patients. However, OGTT is time-consuming and difficult to perform in all PCOS women. In 2010 American Diabetes Association (ADA) endorsed the use of glycated hemoglobin (A1c) for the diagnosis of prediabetes and T2D in general population. However, the efficiency of A1c for prediabetes and T2D diagnosis in PCOS was not well established. OBJETIVE: To evaluate the performance of A1c, blood glucose 0' (BG 0) and blood glucose 120' (BG 120) after OGTT-75g in identifying prediabetes and T2D in a cohort of Brazilian PCOS patients. METHOD(S): 48 premenopausal PCOS women diagnosed by Rotterdam criteria, mean age 27.8-yr (SD+7.0) and BMI 29.9 Kg/m2 (SD+6.4) were selected. An OGTT-75g was performed in all patients. Plasma A1c, serum total cholesterol and its fractions, and testosterone were measured at baseline. Prediabetes and T2D were diagnosed according to the ADA criteria. Levels of agreement between BG 0 BG 120 and A1c LDL, HDL and total T were calculated by Spearman's test. RESULT(S): Obesity/overweight were found in 77% of the patients. Eighteen patients were diagnosed with prediabetes during OGTT: 1 by BG 0 15 by BG 120 and 2 by both tests. Two out of the 18 patients had A1c 5.7-6.4%. The sensitivity of A1c, BG 0 and BG 120 for diagnosing prediabetes was 11% 17% and 83% respectively and the specificity was 100% for all three tests. Three patients were diagnosed with T2D during OGTT by BG 120. One had A1c >6.5% and 2 had A1c levels between 5.7- 6.4%. Sensitivity of A1c and BG 120 for diagnosing T2D was 33% and 100% respectively and the specificity was 100% for both. A1c and BG 0 showed poor strength of agreement for diagnosing prediabetes (k 0.13 p 0.08 and k 0.19 p 0.1 respectively) and T2D (k 0.19 p 0.10 and k 0.48 p 0.30 respectively). BG 120 showed a very good but not significant strength of agreement for diagnosing prediabetes (k 0.85 p 0.88), probably due to the small sample size. A1c and BG 120 demonstrated negative correlation with HDL (r -0.4 and r -0.34 respectively, p<0.05). BG 120 significantly correlated with BMI (r 0.35) and LDL (r 0.39), p < 0.05. A1 and BG 120 did not correlate with total T levels. DISCUSSION: Despite being a young cohort 43.8% of our PCOS patients presented with disturbance of glucose metabolism. A1c was not suitable as screening tool for prediabetes and diabetes in this cohort of Brazilian PCOS patients. BG 120 was a sensitive screening test and presented a significant correlation with HDL, BMI and LDL, reinforcing its role as metabolic risk marker. Our data suggest that OGTTs should be performed in all women with PCOS, which is in line with the AES recommendation.
