T1  - Insulin resistance; HOMA-IR and analytical limitations
T3  - Insulin Resistance Symposium 2017. Izmir Turkey.
A1  - Konukoglu D. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Insulin sensitivity and secretion are reciprocally related. Insulin resistance (IR) can be defined as a impaired biological responce to normal insulin concentrations, thus, IR results in increased insulin secretion to maintain normal glucose and lipid homeostasis. IR is not a disease or specific diagnosis, but it is a common feature of several diseases such as obesity, hypertension, diabetes, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and cardiovascular diseases (CVD). On the other hand the Insulin Resistance Syndrome, called as metabolic syndrome is used to describe the cluster of abnormalities that are more likely to occur in insulin resistant/hyperinsulinemic individuals. Diagnosis of CVD, hypertension, PCOS or acanthosis nigricans, family history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, or CVD, history of gestational diabetes or glucose intolerance, Non-Caucasian ethnicity, sedentary lifestyle, BMI >25.0 kg/m2 (or waist circumference >94 cm (or >102cm) in men, >80 cm (or>88cm) in women and age >40 years are factors that increase the likelihood of the insulin resistance syndrome. There are many potential causes and contributors to insulin resistance. Numerous studies show that high amounts of free fatty acids in the blood, high intake of fructose, increased oxidative stress and inflammation in the body, physical inactivity and disruption in the bacterial environment in the gut. There are also various genetic, social and etnic factors. Hereditary causes include mutations of insulin receptor, glucose transporter, and signaling proteins, although the common forms are largely unidentified. Insulin resistance may be reduced or even completely reversed with simple lifestyle measures, such as exercise, eating healthy, losing belly fat and taking care of sleep and stress levels. In a research setting the euglycemic insulin clamp technique has been considered to be the gold standard and intravenous glucose tolerance test and/or the insulin tolerance test /insulin suppression test are the tests most frequently used. Since these techniques are impractical, Homeostasis model assessment of insulin resistance (HOMA-IR or HOMA) have been used for routine clinical use, and provides a simple estimate of beta-cell function. HOMAIR is derived from the product of the insulin and glucose values divided by a constant, that is, calculated by using the following formula: fasting glucose (mg/dL) X fasting insulin (muU/mL) / 405 (for SI units: fasting glucose (mmol/L) X fasting insulin (muU/L) / 22.5). A value greater than 2.5 indicates insulin resistance. The HOMA method infers the degree of insulin resistance from the basal levels of endogenous insulin and glucose, and shows the steady-state solution of organ-based equations. However, there are numerous criticisms about the use of HOMA-IR, and the most important issue is the lack of standardization of insulin measurements, which makes comparison with other studies or population difficult. It has been suggested that there was a significant effect of age on the diagnostic performance of HOMA-IR levels to identify cardio metabolic risk in non-diabetic women, but not in nondiabetic men. Therefore the effect of age and gender on the ability of HOMA-IR should be taken into account in the estimation of their values in different populations. It is also expected to be different in prepubertal and pubertal children. A transient insulin resistance develops in children during puberty. This insulin resistance emerging during pubertal maturation is accepted as a physiological condition rather than pathologic. The HOMA-IR threshold is rapidly increased when children reach the age of 10 years, when most commence puberty. Therefore, it is important that, in the evaluation of insulin resistance in children and adolescents, different threshold values should be used according to puberty stage or age. Our society, "Society of Clinical Biochemistry Specialists", founded in 1999. Since these date, we have organized several courses, conferences and panels on insulin resistance, diabetes, metabolic syndrome and obesity, and our association aims to lead the researcher in this regard. There is a necessity for initiating and spreading standardization and harmonization studies for insulin determinations throughout the country. An external quality control program of our society, KBUDEK, shows us that action plans have to be drawn up on this issue. The discordance in test results for commercial insulin reagent sets is likely multifactorial and will require a continuing effort to understand the differences and achieve the desired consistency and harmonization among commercial immunoassays.
