329. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 615337578
T1  - Mixed endometrioid and serous endometrial cancer in a young nulliparous woman. A case report of an obese young lady, known to have fibroids of the uterus and PCOD, and had received Depoprovera injection 10 days predating an episode of heavy vaginal bleeding
T3  - Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists World Congress, RCOG 2017. Cape Town South Africa.
A1  - Islam N.
A1  - Ghazi A.
A1  - Hamid T.
A1  - Ayaz A. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Introduction Endometrial cancer is the commonest malignancy of the female genital tract in developed countries, with an incidence of 12.9 per 100 000 women. The average age of diagnosis is 61 years, with only 1.5% occurring at <35 years. The commonest histopathology is endometrioid grade 1 and 2, or type 1 endometrial cancer (80%). Type 2 endometrial cancers, grade 3 endometrioid tumours, as well as tumours of non-endometrioid histology: papillary serous (10%), followed by clear cell (2-4%), mucinous (0.6-5%), and squamous cell (0.1-0.5%) account for 20% of all endometrial cancers, with a mean age of diagnosis of 65 years. Case A 35-year-old, obese, virgin woman with polycystic ovarian syndrome and multiple fibroids of the uterus, presented to the Emergency department with a history of heavy menstrual bleeding. She had a 3-year history of infrequent menstruation. She was admitted for resuscitation and further work up. She continued to bleed, despite medical treatment. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of pelvis showed multiple uterine fibroids, with focal invasion of the myometrium, suggestive of possible malignancy. As she was a virgin, she declined endometrial biopsy and it was a clinical dilemma as to how to manage her further. Hysterectomy was a difficult decision on the basis of suspicious MRI findings, as she was young and had not completed her family. She finally consented to endometrial biopsy, which surprisingly showed serous endometrial cancer. A total abdominal hysterectomy, bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy and omentectomy was carried out and the final pathology showed it to be combined serous (10%) and endometrioid (90%) cancer of the endometrium. Also of note is that during her investigative work up, she was diagnosed to have diabetes, hypertension and a thrombus in the arch of aorta, for which treatment was commenced. Discussion We must harbour a high suspicion of endometrial cancer in obese women with PCOS, and in cases where medical treatment has failed, irrespective of the age of the patient. We should not be misled by other diagnoses like fibroids, and actively look for and exclude ominous conditions like cancer. We should not hesitate to perform an endometrial biopsy in a young, unmarried, virgin patient, who has a high likelihood of endometrial hyperplasia or cancer. Sensitive counselling, and information based on evidence, should overcome this problem. Obese women are at risk of numerous health risks, and as their gynaecologists we must raise awareness of these issues and suggest suitable measures.
