330. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 614089791
T1  - Cost-effectiveness of pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery on obstetric outcomes
T3  - 37th Annual Meeting of the Society for Maternal-Fetal Medicine: The Pregnancy Meeting. Las Vegas, NV United States.
A1  - Luck M.L.
A1  - Cahill A.G.
A1  - Niu B.
A1  - Ameel B.M.
A1  - Caughey A.B. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Almost one third of reproductive age women are obese, which increases the risk of obstetric complications. Bariatric surgery can decrease body mass index (BMI) by 11 kg/m2 potentially reducing the risk of adverse maternal and neonatal outcomes. We sought to determine if bariatric surgery is a cost-effective method to reduce pregnancy complications in obese women. STUDY DESIGN: A decision analytic model using TreeAge software was used to assess the cost-effectiveness of bariatric surgery prior to becoming pregnant in a theoretical cohort of 1,276,000 women that represents the approximate number of obese women age 20-39 in the United States. Outcomes included gestational diabetes (GDM), preeclampsia, preterm delivery (PTD), cesarean delivery, maternal mortality, and neurodevelopmental disability (NDD). All model inputs were derived from the literature. Utilities were included with a discounted life expectancy rate of 3% to produce quality adjusted life years (QALYs). The cost-effectiveness threshold for this model was set at $100,000 per QALY. RESULT(S): Pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery was the preferred (dominant) strategy due to more favorable outcomes as QALYs that compensated for higher costs. This is due to the impact on fecundity from improved ovulation rates after bariatric surgery. Pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery led to lower rates of GDM, preeclampsia, and largefor- gestational-age (LGA) infants. However, these pregnancies had higher rates of PTD, small-for-gestational-age (SGA) infants, cesarean delivery, maternal death and neonates with NDD. The cost of an SGA infant lead to increased cost in the patients who did not have pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery. Univariate sensitivity analyses showed that pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery became the preferred strategy when infertility rates exceed 20%. CONCLUSION(S): Pre-pregnancy bariatric surgery reduces the risk of GDM, preeclampsia and LGA infants. It is a cost-effective strategy for in women who are anovulatory to improve overall pregnancy outcomes. (Figure Presented).
